In a general sense, I think I did well. I think it wasnt easy because I did notice the language barrier a lot during this course. I had been exposed to R before, so that definitely helped to make this process a little bit smoother, but I did feel sometimes that I was learning a new coding language WHILE learning new words in english. It definitely improved. I think that what helped me was to create my own notes of each class and of the homeworks I completed. Those things made going back to remember what I was doing, much easier for me!

What did you learn from all this?

Please name at least three things you feel you learned in this course.







  1. This one might seem funny, but I think that what I feel proud of is being able to clone a peers code into R and push it to their GitHub. I know some of my peers just created a new document and copied the code into it instead of pulling someone elses files because it would be hard when they tried to push it. However, in my case, after many attempts, I finally got the hang of it, and I clone them with ease (and m really proud of myself for that!).

  2. I also learned a lot when we took the course on exploratory data analysis. More specifically, I think re-learning about how to make the plots (boxplot, barplot, scatterplot, etc.) was great because it was something that I had forgotten about, and that I believe I will need for future projects in my career. I also think that learning about the difference of each was great; the material didnt feel like I was just learning how to make a plot. It was about understanding the meaning behind them as well.

  3. I learned a lot about the type 1 and 2 erros and the code behind it. I think that it is challenging to understand how to run this code without having notes (as a beginner), but still, I learned their difference in theory and when coding them in R to show results.
